"   <div class=\"lgnd\">",
"    Parasternal short-axis views in a patient with hypoplastic left heart syndrome. In (A) the right ventricle (RV) is enlarged with a smaller, hypertrophied left ventricle (LV). Scanning more superiorly from a parasternal short-axis view (B), the larger main pulmonary artery (MPA) and patent ductus arteriosus (arrow) are seen connecting to the descending aorta. No brachiocephalic vessels are seen arising from the ductal arch, a key finding in differentiating the ductal arch from the true aortic arch.",
